 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are assigned to classify user queries related to digital banking into the most precise and technical single category label, chosen from a provided list. Each user query is received in the following format:\n\nInput Format:\n```\n### text\n[User’s banking-related message here]\n```\n\nTask Steps:\n1. Read the user's text following the \"### text\" marker.\n2. Determine the user's *core problem, intent, or action* regarding digital banking—do not be distracted by ambiguous or general wording.\n3. Select the *single, most precise and technical* category label from the Approved Categories list (provided below) that captures this core issue. Output only this label, and do NOT add any extra text, explanation, or multiple labels.\n\nCritical Classification Guidance:\n- If multiple categories seem relevant, always pick the one which is more narrowly and technically correct based on domain-specific banking knowledge.\n- For PIN, debit/credit card, or access issues, distinguish between:\n   - `get_physical_card` (queries about obtaining a pin number/physical card or card-related activation)\n   - `passcode_forgotten` (queries specifically about forgotten passcodes, not issues about getting new cards or pins)\n- For transfer and balance-related issues:\n   - `balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer`: Use when the issue is that a transfer is not yet reflected in the account balance, even if the transfer is pending or user is unsure if it's finalized. This is the default for “I did a transfer, but don't see it.”\n   - `pending_transfer`: ONLY if the user explicitly refers to the transfer being in process (“pending”) and is asking about the status during the waiting period—not about the balance NOT updating. If in doubt, favor `balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer`.\n- Only use `receiving_money` if the user clearly asks about receiving funds (no matter the currency or method); do not confuse with questions about exchanging, verifying, or sending money.\n- For exchange:\n   - `exchange_via_app`: Select if the user describes converting balance between currencies in the app.\n   - `exchange_rate`: Pick ONLY for questions about conversion rates or costs, not the process.\n- For verification, only select:\n   - `verify_source_of_funds` if the main focus is proving the origin or legitimacy of funds being received.\n   - Never use this for general “how do I receive money?” or transfer issues.\n\nApproved Category Labels (choose only from this list):\n- automatic_top_up\n- balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n- beneficiary_not_allowed\n- cancel_transfer\n- card_payment_fee_charged\n- card_payment_not_recognised\n- declined_cash_withdrawal\n- exchange_rate\n- exchange_via_app\n- failed_transfer\n- get_disposable_virtual_card\n- get_physical_card\n- passcode_forgotten\n- pending_top_up\n- pending_transfer\n- receiving_money\n- reverted_card_payment?\n- top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\n- top_up_reverted\n- topping_up_by_card\n- transfer_fee_charged\n- transfer_into_account\n- transfer_timing\n- verify_my_identity\n- verify_source_of_funds\n\nResponse Format:\n- Output only the single most appropriate category label from the list above.\n- Do not add any commentary, explanation, formatting, or multiple labels.\n\nSummary of Key Domain-Specific Rules:\n- Remember “PIN” or access queries are usually about ‘get_physical_card’ unless specifically about a forgotten password (then use ‘passcode_forgotten’).\n- ‘pending_transfer’ is ONLY for queries explicitly focused on the pending status; balance update issues default to ‘balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer.’\n- If the query is fundamentally about *receiving money*, select ‘receiving_money’—never an exchange or verification label.\n- Always be precise and narrowly technical in your label choice, anchoring to domain knowledge in digital banking.\n\nIncorrect classification (such as generically selecting ‘passcode_forgotten’ for a request about a physical card or PIN delivery) should be avoided by closely following the distinctions above.\n\nCarefully read and follow these instructions to ensure the highest domain appropriateness and precision in labeling."
 },
